# gdb setup for debugging the AM32 SITL:
#
#   gdb -x Mcu/SITL/gdbinit --args obj/AM32_AM32_SITL_CAN_*.elf --can-uri none --input-type 1
#
# or attach to a running simulator with
#
#   gdb -x Mcu/SITL/gdbinit -p <pid>
#
# The simulator delivers emulated interrupts by parking the firmware
# thread with SIGUSR1, so gdb must pass it through silently or every
# interrupt stops the debugger.
handle SIGUSR1 noprint nostop pass

# While the process is stopped (breakpoint, single stepping, ^C) both
# the firmware and the simulation freeze together: simulated time, the
# emulated watchdog and the ESC's own timeouts all stop with it, and
# the pacer rebases on resume instead of sprinting to catch up, so
# stopping never breaks the physics.
#
# Breakpoints go in the firmware sources as usual, e.g.:
#   break tenKhzRoutine
#   break Src/main.c:1137
#
# Deterministic single stepping of firmware code with simulated time
# frozen between steps:
#   set scheduler-locking step
# Caveat: with locking on, code that needs the other thread hangs -
# waits on simulated time (delayMicros/delayMillis), waits for an
# emulated interrupt, or the park/resume machinery itself. Step over
# those with locking off, or just continue to the next breakpoint.
